{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472047"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:54:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:54:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"954"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/954"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.03,0.71,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/954"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26757"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"584"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2080"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12432"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA mother presents with her seven-year-old son to the General Practice clinic worried that her child is eating too much and is putting on too much weight. She has been trying to serve him smaller portion sizes at mealtimes but notices that he is always looking around in the fridge for more food. She has heard from his teachers at school that he is stealing food from other children, and has been caught attempting to eat discarded food from the rubbish bin. His developmental history is significant for hypotonia at birth, having a mild intellectual disability and difficult behaviour including frequent temper tantrums. There is no known significant family history. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn inspection, the child appears mildly agitated, with prominent truncal obesity, almond-shaped eyes, flat nasal bridge, up-turned nose, smooth philtrum, a thin upper lip, and small hands and feet. He becomes distressed during an attempt to measure his height or weight and refuses any further examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome","Cushing\u0027s syndrome","Bardet-Biedl syndrome","Prader-Willi syndrome","Trisomy 21"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child is manifesting the characteristic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EPrader-Willi syndrome (PWS). \u003C/strong\u003EPWS is an uncommon genetic disorder, affecting about 1 in 10,000 births, typified by voracious appetite in childhood with pronounced compulsive eating behaviours and resulting weight gain. Other features include neonatal hypotonia with resulting feeding difficulty (often requiring nasogastric feeding), global developmental delay with cognitive impairment, behavioural issues including tantrums and extreme stubbornness, hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism, and phenotypic facial and extremity abnormalities. PWS is a notable example of the epigenetic phenomenon of \u0027genomic imprinting\u0027, arising when a congenital deletion occurs in a region of the paternal chromosome 15 (region 15q11), for which the maternal allele cannot compensate because the expression of this region is blocked via imprinting. If instead the maternal allele is affected, the completely distinct Angelman syndrome results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeckwith-Wiedemann syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a cause of secondary childhood obesity, however it is generally not known to involve such prominent behavioural abnormalities. It is associated with macroglossia, hemi-hypertrophy, neonatal anterior abdominal wall defects such as an omphalocoele, Wilms tumour and neonatal hypoglycaemia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELikewise, \u003Cstrong\u003ECushing\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with behavioural abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBardet-Biedl syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal recessive disorder characterised by childhood obesity. However, it most commonly presents with polyuria and polydipsia due to nephrogenic diabetes inspidus. Other features include hypogonadism in men, mental retardation, polydactyly, retinal dystrophy and renal malformations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile children with \u003Cstrong\u003EDown\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E are at a higher risk of obesity than the general population, it is not a classical feature. Down\u0027s syndrome is a cause of neonatal hypotonia and global developmental delay, but it is unlikely to cause such extreme food-seeking behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Key findings in Prader-Willi syndrome in childhood include hyperphagia, endocrine abnormalities, and cognitive-behavioural issues","Infants with Prader-Willi typically manifest hypotonia, feeding difficulty, failure to thrive, and hypogonadism."],"references":["Butler MG, Miller JL, Forster JL. Prader-Willi Syndrome - Clinical Genetics, Diagnosis and Treatment Approaches: An Update. Curr Pediatr Rev. 2019;15(4):207-244. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7040524/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26757"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"954"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26757"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-23T21:07:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-23T21:07:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"954"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"des